lu_part1: Wien A seet, muss och B soen.
en_literal_p1: If A sees, B must also say.
en_correct_p1: If one person sees, another must also say.

lu_part1: Wann d'Aarbecht ee räich méich, da wier den Iesel méi räich wéi de Mëller.
en_literal_p1: When work makes one rich, the donkey becomes richer than the miller.
en_correct_p1: When work makes one rich, the donkey becomes richer than the miller.

lu_part1: Vun der Aarbecht gëtt kee fett.
en_literal_p1: From work, no one gets fat.
en_correct_p1: From work, no one gets fat.

lu_part1: Dat Aalt dauert am längsten.
en_literal_p1: The old lasts the longest.
en_correct_p1: The old lasts the longest.

lu_part1: Besser e midden Aarm, wéi een eidelen Daarm.
en_literal_p1: Better a poor arm than a noble intestine.
en_correct_p1: Better a poor arm than a noble intestine.

lu_part1: Aarm sinn ass keng Schan.
en_literal_p1: Poorness is not a shame.
en_correct_p1: Poorness is not a shame.

lu_part1: D'Aarmut ass e Sträitmécher.
en_literal_p1: Poverty is a quarrel maker.
en_correct_p1: Poverty is a quarrel maker.

lu_part1: Hien huet mech net emol mam Aasch bekuckt (hien huet mech total ignoréiert).
en_literal_p1: He didn't even look at me with his eyes (he completely ignored me).
en_correct_p1: He didn't even look at me with his eyes (he completely ignored me).

lu_part1: Adam an Éiv waren déi zwéin éischt Äppeldéif.
en_literal_p1: Adam and Eve were the first two apple thieves.
en_correct_p1: Adam and Eve were the first two apple thieves.

lu_part1: Aus den Aen, aus dem Sënn.
en_literal_p1: Out of the eyes, out of the mind.
en_correct_p1: Out of the eyes, out of the mind.

lu_part1: Véier Ae gesi méi wéi zwee.
en_literal_p1: Four eyes see more than two.
en_correct_p1: Four eyes see more than two.

lu_part1: D'Aen op oder de Beidel.
en_literal_p1: The eyes up or the bag.
en_correct_p1: The eyes up or the bag.

lu_part1: Wat een net ännere kann, soll ee roueg erdroen.
en_literal_p1: What one cannot change, one should calmly endure.
en_correct_p1: What one cannot change, one should calmly endure.

lu_part1: Näischt gesot ass och eng Äntwert.
en_literal_p1: Nothing said is also an answer.
en_correct_p1: Nothing said is also an answer.

lu_part1: Een Af mécht der honnert.
en_literal_p1: One monkey makes a hundred.
en_correct_p1: One monkey makes a hundred.

lu_part1: Engem Af geet alles gutt.
en_literal_p1: Everything tastes good to a monkey.
en_correct_p1: Everything tastes good to a monkey.

lu_part1: Ech ginn der gläich en Akkont! (du kriss gläich Streech!).
en_literal_p1: I'll give you an account right away! (you'll get a fight right away!).
en_correct_p1: I'll give you an account right away! (you'll get a fight right away!).

lu_part1: Léier keen alen Af Grimasse maachen.
en_literal_p1: Don't let an old monkey make grimaces.
en_correct_p1: Don't let an old monkey make grimaces.

lu_part1: Al Eisen, ale Goss, al Fraen, ale Verdross.
en_literal_p1: All iron, all goose, all women, all annoyance.
en_correct_p1: All iron, all goose, all women, all annoyance.

lu_part1: En ale Kniecht an eng jonk Mod gëtt gär e grousse Stot.
en_literal_p1: An old servant and a young girl get a big push.
en_correct_p1: An old servant and a young girl get a big push.

lu_part1: Bei den Alen ass ee gutt gehalen.
en_literal_p1: With the old, one is well held.
en_correct_p1: With the old, one is well held.

lu_part1: Alles leeft, nëmmen de Fräsch deen hopst.
en_literal_p1: Everything lives, only the frog jumps.
en_correct_p1: Everything lives, only the frog jumps.

lu_part1: Den Alter geet vir (sot den Eilespill, dunn huet e seng Mamm d'Trap eragestouss).
en_literal_p1: The old goes away (said the squirrel, then his mother pushed the door open).
en_correct_p1: The old goes away (said the squirrel, then his mother pushed the door open).

lu_part1: An Amen a Jo war d'Affär gedoen (d'Affär war ganz séier gedoen).
en_literal_p1: In Amen and Jo, the affair was done (the affair was done very quickly).
en_correct_p1: In Amen and Jo, the affair was done (the affair was done very quickly).

lu_part1: Sécher wéi den Amen am Gebiet.
en_literal_p1: As sure as the Amen in the prayer.
en_correct_p1: As sure as the Amen in the prayer.

lu_part1: Den Apel fält net wäit vum Bam, e misst just de Bierg erofrullen.
en_literal_p1: The apple doesn't fall far from the tree, it just has to roll down the hill.
en_correct_p1: The apple doesn't fall far from the tree, it just has to roll down the hill.

lu_part1: Et soll ee sech ëmmer een Apel fir den Duuscht versuergen.
en_literal_p1: One should always save an apple for thirst.
en_correct_p1: One should always save an apple for thirst.

lu_part1: Den Appetit kënnt iwwer dem Iessen.
en_literal_p1: Appetite comes while eating.
en_correct_p1: Appetite comes while eating.

lu_part1: D'Ausriede si fir ze gebrauchen.
en_literal_p1: The excuses are for use.
en_correct_p1: The excuses are for use.

lu_part1: Bal ass nach keng Maus an der Fal.
en_literal_p1: Soon, there is no mouse in the trap.
en_correct_p1: Soon, there is no mouse in the trap.

lu_part1: Besser den Aascht fält wéi de Bam.
en_literal_p1: Better the branch falls than the tree.
en_correct_p1: Better the branch falls than the tree.

lu_part1: En ale Bam verplanzt een net (en ale Mënsch soll een do liewe loossen, wou e gewinnt ass).
en_literal_p1: An old tree is not transplanted (an old person should be left where they are).
en_correct_p1: An old tree is not transplanted (an old person should be left where they are).

lu_part1: Déi dommst Baueren hunn déi déckst Gromperen (och domm Leit kënne Chance hunn).
en_literal_p1: The dumbest farmers have the thickest potatoes (dumb people can also have luck).
en_correct_p1: The dumbest farmers have the thickest potatoes (dumb people can also have luck).

lu_part1: Wat de Bauer net kennt, dat frësst en net.
en_literal_p1: What the farmer doesn't know, he doesn't eat.
en_correct_p1: What the farmer doesn't know, he doesn't eat.

lu_part1: E Bauer, e Béier an e Stéier, dat sinn dräi ongemälleg Déier.
en_literal_p1: A farmer, a Bavarian, and a Styrian, these are three incompatible animals.
en_correct_p1: A farmer, a Bavarian, and a Styrian, these are three incompatible animals.

lu_part1: Et ass dofir gesuergt, datt d'Beem net an den Himmel wuessen.
en_literal_p1: It is ensured that the trees do not grow into the sky.
en_correct_p1: It is ensured that the trees do not grow into the sky.

lu_part1: Wat een net am Kapp huet, muss een an de Been hunn.
en_literal_p1: What one doesn't have in the head, one must have in the legs.
en_correct_p1: What one doesn't have in the head, one must have in the legs.

lu_part1: Wéi e beicht, sou gëtt ee lassgesprach.
en_literal_p1: As one confesses, one is spoken to.
en_correct_p1: As one confesses, one is spoken to.

lu_part1: Wéi een an de Bësch rifft, sou schaalt et erëm.
en_literal_p1: As one calls into the forest, it echoes back.
en_correct_p1: As one calls into the forest, it echoes back.

lu_part1: Dat bescht kënnt hannenno.
en_literal_p1: The best comes from behind.
en_correct_p1: The best comes from behind.

lu_part1: Besser ass besser, sot d'Fra, do huet se d'Ham an der Mëllech gekacht.
en_literal_p1: Better is better, said the woman, then she bought the ham in the milk.
en_correct_p1: Better is better, said the woman, then she bought the ham in the milk.

lu_part1: Besser eng Kuuscht an der Täsch, wéi eng Fieder um Hutt.
en_literal_p1: Better a kiss in the pocket than a feather on the hat.
en_correct_p1: Better a kiss in the pocket than a feather on the hat.

lu_part1: Besser spéit eppes, wéi fréi näischt.
en_literal_p1: Better late something than early nothing.
en_correct_p1: Better late something than early nothing.

lu_part1: Besser spéit, wéi guer net.
en_literal_p1: Better late than never.
en_correct_p1: Better late than never.

lu_part1: D'Bestueden ass eng Lotterie.
en_literal_p1: The burial is a lottery.
en_correct_p1: The burial is a lottery.

lu_part1: Wéi ee säi Bett mécht, sou schléift een.
en_literal_p1: As one makes their bed, they sleep.
en_correct_p1: As one makes their bed, they sleep.

lu_part1: Et ass besser biedelen, wéi stielen.
en_literal_p1: It is better to beg than to steal.
en_correct_p1: It is better to beg than to steal.

lu_part1: Hanner dem Bierg sinn och Leit.
en_literal_p1: Behind the mountain are also people.
en_correct_p1: Behind the mountain are also people.

lu_part1: En neie Biesem kiert besser.
en_literal_p1: A new broom sweeps better.
en_correct_p1: A new broom sweeps better.

lu_part1: Och eng blann Sau kann eng Eechel fannen.
en_literal_p1: Even a blind sow can find an acorn.
en_correct_p1: Even a blind sow can find an acorn.

lu_part1: Et ass nach laang net alles Gold, wat blénkt.
en_literal_p1: Not everything that shines is gold.
en_correct_p1: Not everything that shines is gold.

lu_part1: Et heescht keng Kou Blimmchen, dees se hief eng wäiss Strimmchen.
en_literal_p1: There is no cow flower that doesn't have a white stripe.
en_correct_p1: There is no cow flower that doesn't have a white stripe.

lu_part1: Mengen a Botter schäissen ass zweeërlee.
en_literal_p1: Mixing and buttering are two different things.
en_correct_p1: Mixing and buttering are two different things.

lu_part1: Du bass net hei, fir brong ze ginn! (seet een zu engem, deen net effikass schafft).
en_literal_p1: You are not here to be brought! (said to someone who doesn't work effectively).
en_correct_p1: You are not here to be brought! (said to someone who doesn't work effectively).

lu_part1: Deen nervt mech, ech kéint en ongespëtzt an de Buedem schloen! (deen nervt mech, ech géif en am léifste gutt zerschloen).
en_literal_p1: He annoys me, I could beat him to a pulp! (he annoys me, I would gladly smash him).
en_correct_p1: He annoys me, I could beat him to a pulp! (he annoys me, I would gladly smash him).
